SIMPLE: avenue
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Avenue
<hw>Av"e*nue</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>avenue</ets>, fr. <ets>avenir</ets> to come to, L.
<ets>advenire</ets>. See <er>Advene</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A way
or opening for entrance into a place; a passage by which a place may by
reached; a way of approach or of exit.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>avenues</xex> leading to the city by land.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On every side were expanding new <qex>avenues</qex> of
inquiry.</q> <rj><qau>Milman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The principal walk or approach to a house which is
withdrawn from the road, especially, such approach bordered on each side
by trees; any broad passageway thus bordered.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>avenue</qex> of tall elms and branching chestnuts.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A broad street; <as>as, the Fifth <ex>Avenue</ex> in
New York</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Aver</ent>⟦br⟧
